# Native Android App Conversion Walkthrough

Your React web app has been successfully transformed into a native Android app architecture using **Capacitor**! 

Here is what was accomplished:
- Installed Capacitor core libraries in your React project.
- Initialized the configuration (`capacitor.config.json`) with the bundle ID `com.appterra.fundraiser`.
- Built the production-ready React web code into the `dist` folder.
- Generated a native `android` folder right inside your project directory.
- Synced the web assets into the Android native wrapper.

## Next Steps: Compiling the APK

Your project now contains a folder named `android` which is a complete, native Android Studio project.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Any time you make changes to your React app in the future (like editing `App.jsx`), you need to run two commands to push those changes to the Android app:
> 1. `npm run build`
> 2. `npx cap sync`

### Open in Android Studio

To open the project in Android Studio and compile it into an app you can install on your phone, open your terminal (inside the `Fundraiser` folder) and run:

```bash
npx cap open android
```

Alternatively, you can manually open **Android Studio**, click "Open", and select the `android` folder located inside `c:\Users\Anees Ahad\Desktop\Desktop PVT\Fundraiser\`.

### Building the APK
Once Android Studio opens the project and finishes syncing (this might take a few minutes as it downloads Gradle dependencies):
1. Wait for the indexing and Gradle sync to finish completely.
2. In the top menu, click **Build > Build Bundle(s) / APK(s) > Build APK(s)**.
3. Once it finishes, a small pop-up will appear in the bottom right corner with a "locate" link. 
4. Click that link, and you will find your `app-debug.apk` file ready to be transferred to your phone and installed!
